{
  "doc_id": "10110",
  "text": "Through a large-scale phylogenomic analysis on 174 proteomes, Caetano-Anollés and co-workers established a chronology for proteins, in which 776 folds are recorded according to their evolutionary order, respectively. (http://www.manet.uiuc.edu/ download/foldAncestryVal2_0.txt) [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . According to the evolutionary sequence of 776 folds, Ferredoxin-like (d.58) is No. 5. It is interesting to note that this fold is indeed one of the earliest protein architectures. However, there are still four kinds of folds appeared earlier than d.58. How did the proteins of these four folds appear?",
